channel closure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eselective potassium permeability\u003C/strong\u003E through specific membrane channels is fundamental in establishing the resting potential. The high density of potassium channels facilitate potassium ions moving out of the cell along their concentration gradient, creating the negative internal charge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive chloride transport mechanisms\u003C/strong\u003E do not determine the resting potential as chloride distributes passively and is not actively moved across the membrane. \u003Cstrong\u003EConstant sodium ion entry\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur because sodium permeability is very low at rest. \u003Cstrong\u003EBalanced sodium and potassium flow\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since the membrane is much more permeable to potassium than sodium in the resting state. \u003Cstrong\u003EComplete ion channel closure\u003C/strong\u003E would prevent the establishment of membrane potential as ion channels must remain selectively open to maintain it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium-potassium ATPase pump establishes the ion gradients, but the resting potential of -70 mV results from the selective permeability to potassium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The resting membrane potential is primarily determined by potassium leak channels in the cell membrane.","Selective ion permeability and concentration gradients establish the negative internal charge of neurons.","The sodium-potassium pump maintains ion gradients but does not directly set the membrane potential."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 5; pg. 66","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{